#257 Misc
    :date: 2026-03-05 13:15
    :shortdes: Tailscale
    :tags: Tech

.(<em>If you don't know anything about networking, use multiple computers on a
daily basis, write code, run servers, etc., this will be uninteresting. If you
do, and you haven't heard of Tailscale, this might be one of the most useful
things you've read in a while!</em>)

.<a href="https://tailscale.com/">Tailscale</a> has been a thing for a few
years now, but I never quite took the time to look into it and understand what
it did. Recently, Claude recommended it to me to solve a specific problem, and
having started using it, I am upset I waited this long – it's been a huge
quality-of-life improvement!

.Basically, Tailscale allows you to set up – for free, for up to 3 users, and
for a very reasonable price if you need more complex security and identity
management – a virtual local network that can be composed of, essentially, any
devices connected to the internet, anywhere. You install one piece of software
and log in on each device, and…that's it. I can access my desktop computer or
my file server network from a coffee shop halfway across the world. Or for that
matter, access my laptop on mobile hotspot from my desktop! No NAT
configuration, no dynamic DNS, no SSH tunneling, no extra public server, no
attack surface created by punching holes in a firewall, it just magically
works. You can directly connect to things when you're off-LAN using the same
IPs you would use on the LAN (and there are other routing and hostname options
too if you need them).

.You can also configure most devices as “exit nodes” and allow internet traffic
to be bounced through them from any other device, if you need to get around
geolocation blocks that require you to be “at home” or you're on a sketchy
network and want an extra layer of protection.

.It took me a couple of hours to get my network set up, but almost all of that
time was spent getting the unsupported configuration of Tailscale on a FreeBSD
NAS serving files via NFS working. If your network configuration is even
slightly more normal than mine, it would probably take you all of 20 minutes to
get everything working.

.If you have a hacky system for doing any of this, or if you don't have the
ability to use your home devices when you're away from home because it feels
like too much work to set up, check it out.


